ce**."\n*   **Implication:** This confirms that a major part of the AI capex is being capitalized on the balance sheet as CIP. It only begins to depreciate (i.e., impacts the income statement as an expense) once it is completed and "placed in service" to support operations.\n\n### 3. Expected Timeline for Infrastructure to Begin Depreciating\nThe documents do not provide an explicit calendar timeline for when specific assets will move from CIP to "in service." However, the business context provides a clear indicative timeline:\n\n*   **The "Multi-Year Investment Horizon":** The company states it expects a "multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA." This implies that the transition of these assets from construction to operational use (and thus the start of depreciation) will be a gradual process occurring over the next several years.\n*   **Operational Trigger:** The key trigger is when the data centers are "equipped" and "placed in service" to support AI product development and inference services (like Grok). The massive Q1 2026 and 2025 capex figures suggest large blocks of infrastructure will come online in phases through 2026 and 2027.\n\n### 4. Guidance on Future Depreciation Trends\nThere is no explicit forward-looking guidance on depreciation amounts. However, the trend can be strongly inferred from the capex and CIP data:\n\n*   **Depreciation Will Rise Sharply:** As the enormous investments currently in CIP are completed and placed in service, they will begin to depreciate. This means depreciation expense is **projected to increase substantially in future periods**, directly following the multi-billion dollar capex ramps.\n*   **Historical Trend is Clear:** Depreciation expense has already grown significantly in line with prior capex:\n    *   **2025:** $5,915 million\n    *   **2024:** $2,977 million\n    *   **2023:** (Amount not provided in snippets, but implied to be lower)\n    *   **Q1 2026:** $2,329 million (suggesting 2026 annual depreciation will exceed 2025)\n*   **Segment-Level Impact:** The AI segment\'s supplemental depreciation expense shows this trend clearly:\n    *   **2025:** $1,679 million\n    *   **2024:** $1,180 million\n    *   **2023:** $1,081 million\n    *   **Q1 2026:** $1,493 million (indicating a sharp increase for the year).\n\n**Summary:** The company is in a phase of "hyper-scaling" its AI infrastructure, with most capital being directed to terrestrial data centers. A large portion of this spend is currently in Construction-in-Progress. As these assets come online over the next few years, they will begin to depreciate, leading to a significant and predictable increase in depreciation expense across the company and within the AI segment specifically. This depreciation will be a major component of the "multi-year investment horizon" before the segment reaches sustainable profitability.',
